begin_memory_text: At the beginning of the conversation, my partner mentioned that she had just finished home schooling her kindergartner, and that she could use a break and a 'chance to talk to an adult'. We then started talking about her kids and what grades they were in and what their current school setup was.
middle_memory_text: We both talked about our approaches to dealing with kids during the pandemic and strategies for getting together with other kids, visiting friends and family, and how comfortable we were with different activities in public.
end_memory_text: We talked about one of the challenges of schooling in person - with my recent experience of my kids getting a cold and how that resulted in needing COVID testing.
rest_of_day_open: I have a busy next couple of days, with some doctor appointments and a lot of work to squeeze in, often with kids around. I feel good about having the work though, since some of it will be overtime, and I welcome the chance to help support my family financially and help pay some recent bills that were significant.
critical_positive: THe fact that we had so much in common. We both have kids in similar age groups and going through altered school schedules (her kids remote and mine in a hybrid schedule). We could swap a lot of stories about our recent experiences that the other person could totally relate to, as well as offer each other advice and encouragement during this interesting time.
critical_negative: At first, I thought that my partner seemed a little bit negative or pessimistic, so I remember thinking that this might be a challenging or less than enjoyable conversation. However, as we talked more I felt more of an openness and more positivity coming from them. Then I felt bad that I had sort of judged them at the start of the conversation.

begin_memory_text: We started by talking about our daily routine during home schooling/stay at home orders. We found that we both work from home and have kids in similar grades.
middle_memory_text: We discussed how things have changed for our families and talked about how we handle social interactions. We agreed it's difficult to have these discussions about whether or not it's safe to play with other kids. There are no easy answers to how to handle these interactions.
end_memory_text: We talked a little more about school protocols towards screening students for illness. We also talked about prolific and our experiences with taking surveys/doing this chat.
rest_of_day_open: I think it's going to be fine. I have a few more days of working from home/remote school with my kids until the weekend. The weather is still nice so I can be outside still. I've planned ahead to finish tasks/chores that I have to do so I don't feel burdened or underwater on my to-do list.
critical_positive: I think we had a lot of things in common and similar life experiences. I didn't even tell her some of the things I noticed we have in common, but the conversation was nice because we got along well. It helped that we seemed to have a similar philosophy on current issues. She was friendly and casual and made the chat easy.
critical_negative: I think any interaction when you've never met each other and don't know anything about the other can feel awkward and a little forced. I think it could have been a poor experience had we not had enough in common. We occasionally talked over each other, but did get better at reading each others speech patterns and giving each other room to talk.
